pr_body:
[WIP] Extension to this [PR](https://github.com/LalitChauhan56/TestPackage.jl/pull/9) which creates the `@compound` macro with the [updated input.](https://github.com/LalitChauhan56/TestPackage.jl/pull/9#issuecomment-1629558885). Also adds the `iscompound()` function to check if a species is a compound or not. 

```
julia>@variables t
@parameters k
@species C(t) H(t) O(t)

julia>@compound C6H12O2(t) 6C 12H 2O 
3-element Vector{Num}:
  6C(t)
 12H(t)
  2O(t)

julia> iscompound(C6H12O2)
true
```

pr_body:
This adds the functionality of creating a balanced Catalyst reaction.
All we need to do is define the parameters and variables, no need to define the species using the @species macro as they are created automatically! :)
We need to give the input of the reaction in a string format and the create_balanced_reaction function uses it to create a catalyst reaction and automatically balances it stoichiometrically.

Example usage -
```
@parameters k
@variables t

julia> reaction = create_balanced_reaction("CO2 + H2O --> C6H12O6 + O2")
k, 6CO2 + 6H2O --> C6H12O6 + 6*O2

julia> typeof(reaction)
Reaction{Any, Int64}

julia> rn = Catalyst.make_empty_network()
Model ##ReactionSystem#295
States (0):
Parameters (0):

julia> addreaction!(rn,reaction)
1

julia> reactions(rn)
1-element Vector{Reaction}:
k, 6CO2 + 6H2O --> C6H12O6 + 6*O2
```

pr_body:
Can be used to define compounds which are composed of smaller species. The created compound is also a species.

```
julia> @variables t
@parameters k
@species C(t) H(t) O(t) #Define species

julia> @compound C6H12O2(t),[6C,12H,2O] #Creates a compound(also a species in itself)
3-element Vector{Num}:
  6C(t)
 12H(t)
  2O(t)
  
julia> iscompound(C6H12O2)
true
```
